**Abstract:**
A variant of "Speech Acts Again" dated May 1, 1996 critiquing Searle's theory. Opens with Carr quote on narrative as form of life. Develops the map analogy for practical knowledge and argues statements aim at practical disposition rather than intellectual assent. Uses "Your house is burning" example to show statements have perlocutionary effects Searle misses by treating them as pictures.

**AI Recommendation:** Variant of 96-MAY-1; compare for textual differences.

